# Approach
Initialize two pointers, i and j, both pointing to the first and second characters of the string s, respectively.

Use a while loop to iterate through the string while j is within the valid index range (0 to s.length() - 1).

Check if the characters at indices i and j are the same. If they are, it means we have found a duplicate pair.

When a duplicate pair is found, use the erase function to remove both characters from the string s. Since the erase function modifies the string in place, the characters at indices i and j will be removed.

Adjust the pointers i and j to continue searching for adjacent duplicates:

Move i one step back (i = max(0, i - 1)) to check if there are any duplicates before the previously deleted pair.
Move j one step back (j = max(1, j - 1)) to continue the search from the updated position of i.
If the characters at indices i and j are different, move both pointers i and j one step forward to check the next pair of characters.

Repeat steps 3 to 6 until all characters in the string have been checked.

Return the updated string after all adjacent duplicates have been removed.
