# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
> Using stack to get the immediate previous character in the string

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Start a loop for each character in the string 
2. Check if the stack is empty, or if the peeked element from the stack is not equals to the present character in the string, then add the element in the stack
3. In the else condition pop the last element in the stack becase in this case, the last element and the present character is equal to each other.
4. Initialize a char array of `stack.size()` length
5. Pop the elements if the stack while it isnt empty and insert the characters in the array in the `reverse` order.
6. Convert the char array to String and return it.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(N)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(N)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public String removeDuplicates(String s) {
        Stack<Character> stack = new Stack<>();
        for(char ch: s.toCharArray()){
            if(stack.isEmpty() || stack.peek() != ch) stack.add(ch);
            else stack.pop();
        }
        char[] arr = new char[stack.size()];
        for(int i=stack.size(); i>0; i--) arr[i-1] = stack.pop();
        return new String(arr);
    }
}
```

