solutions.content:
The main idea is to have a sliding window of 3 elements and a sum that adds the last bit of the numbers. 
If a number is even, last bit is 0, if odd, last bit is 1. It is similar with having ```x % 2``` but ```x & 1``` is faster.
If the sum is 3, we return true as we found 3 numbers that are odd.

```
class Solution {
    public boolean threeConsecutiveOdds(int[] arr) {
        # Return false if array is null or does not have at least 3 elements
        if (arr == null || arr.length < 3)
            return false;

        # Compute the sum for the first 3 elements
        int moving_sum = last_bit(arr[0]) + last_bit(arr[1]) + last_bit(arr[2]);

		# Return true if the first 3 elements are odd
        if (moving_sum == 3)
            return true;

		# Search for 3 consecutive odd numbers - sliding window
        for (int i = 3; i < arr.length; i++) {
            moving_sum -= last_bit(arr[i-3]);
            moving_sum += last_bit(arr[i]);
            if (moving_sum == 3)
                return true;
        }

		# If no such elements, return false
        return false;
    }

	# Return the last bit of the number
	# Similar with : x % 2
    private int last_bit(int x) {
        return x & 1;
    }
}
```

