Yeah I know that Math solution is great but as a normal person with a normal brain I don't think i can ever come up with that solution in time limited interviews. So let's just try DP

1. Naive thoughts

So we want to find this floor F. At first glance i really thought this is a binary search problem: you drop your first egg at middle floor, if break drop another at lower levels, otherwise higher levels. However, we only have 2 eggs! So when you have lost your first egg at level M, you HAVE TO use the only left egg and try from floor 1 all the way to floor M - 1 to get your answer. With limited supply of eggs, binary search won't work.

Then i thought: ok screw this, don't try to be a smart ass. Let's try to solve this in the brute force way. What is it? You want to know the floor F? OK then i will calculate the result on EVERY SINGLE FLOOR. That is, i am going to calculate how many steps i need to decide floor F if I drop my first egg at 1st floor, how many steps i need to decide floor F if I drop my first egg at 2nd floor, how many steps i need to decide floor F if I drop my first egg at 3rd floor... etc. This sounds like a bulky solution, but this is brute force. Let me work this out then try to optimize it.

2. Implement the brute force

So apparently we need an 2D DP array for this. With each column being the number of floors of the building, and each row being the floor i am gonna drop my first egg. That is `dp[row][col] = the minimum steps i need to take to decide the floor F we are trying to find, if this building has [col] floors, and if I drop my first egg at floor [row]`
Also let's have another array `bests`, where `best[i] = the minimum steps to determine floor F on a building with i floors`. `bests[10] = the minimum steps to determine floor F on a building with 10 floors`
(if you cannot understand why we need `bests`, keep reading. I didn't think we need `bests` in the first place either, but as I proceed with this approach, it occurs to me we need `bests`)
With that determined, for each `dp[row][col]` there are 2 conditions we need to calculate: 
1. what if I drop my first egg at floor row and it breaks (ah oh)
2. what if I drop my first egg at floor row and it survived?

For first case, you will lose your first egg and you only have 1 egg left. Then you will need to drop your last egg from floor 1, then floor 2, then floor 3 all the way to floor row - 1 -- you don't have other choices!
So for case 1, the unlucky case, we need (for the worst case) `1(the initial drop) + (row - 1) (number of drops for your last egg)` .
For second case, nice you didn't lose your first egg. Then the problem evolves from "find floor F on this building with [col] floors" to "find floor F on this building with [col - row] floors". That is, because on floor [row] your egg didn't break, so you don't even need to look at floors below [row]th floor any more -  your egg definitely won't break on these floors. So with this building only has [col - row] floors and 2 eggs in your pocket, we can determine floor F in `bests[col - row]` steps (recall `bests` is `bests[i] = the minimum steps to determine floor F on a building with i floors`, and now, `i` is `col - row`).

Ok, for case 1, we have
`int steps_case_1 = 1 + row - 1 // first egg broke at first drop`
for case 2 we have
`int steps_case_2 = 1 + bests[col - row] // first egg didn't break`
You need to consider both cases, so
`dp[row][col] = max(steps_case_1, steps_case_2)`

Then we keep adding row and col until we fill all spots in our `dp` matrix.

The answer would be `bests[n]`

```
class Solution {
public:
\xA0\xA0\xA0 int twoEggDrop(int n) {
\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0 vector<int> bests(n + 1);
\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0 
\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0 vector<int> oneRow(n + 1);
\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0 vector<vector<int>> dp(n + 1, oneRow);
\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0 
\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0 dp[1][1] = 1; // a building with 1 floor, and i drop at 1st floor
\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0 dp[1][2] = 2; // a building with 2 floors, and i drop at 1st floor
\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0 dp[2][2] = 2; // a building with 2 floors, and i drop at 2nd floor
\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0 
\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0 bests[0] = 0;
\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0 bests[1] = 1;
\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0 bests[2] = 2;
\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0 
\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0 for (int col = 3; col <= n; ++col) {
\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0 int bestThisCol = n; // the mini steps needed to determine floor F if this building has col floors
\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0 for (int row = 1; row <= col; ++row) { // I drop at each floor
\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0 // row is which floor we drop
\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0 // col is the number of floors of this building
\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0 
\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0 // if we have col floors and we drop at rowth floor and it broke
\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0 int breaks = 1 + row - 1;
\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0 // if we have col floors and we drop at rowth floor and it survived
\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0 int survive = 1 + bests[col - row];
\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0 dp[row][col] = max(breaks, survive);
				// with all the floors you can drop your first egg, of cource you will choose the floor so that you can determine F with minimum steps, so this is min() here
\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0 bestThisCol = min(bestThisCol, dp[row][col]);
\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0 }
\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0 bests[col] = bestThisCol;
\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0 }
\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0 
\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0\xA0 return bests[n];
\xA0\xA0\xA0 }
};

```

3. Optimize
Well if you look at above code, you will directly notice we don't need `dp` at all!
```
dp[row][col] = max(breaks, survive);
bestThisCol = min(bestThisCol, dp[row][col]);
```
can be rewriitten as 
```
bestThisCol = min(bestThisCol, max(breaks, survive));
```
So uhhhh, let's dump that `dp`
```
class Solution {
public:
    int twoEggDrop(int n) {
        vector<int> bests(n + 1);

        bests[0] = 0;
        bests[1] = 1;
        bests[2] = 2;

        for (int col = 3; col <= n; ++col) {
            int bestThisCol = n;
            for (int row = 1; row <= col; ++row) {
                // row is which floor we drop
                // col is the number of floors

                // if we have col floors and we drop at rowth floor and it broke
                int breaks = 1 + row - 1;
                // if we have col floors and we drop at rowth floor and it survived
                int survive = 1 + bests[col - row];
                bestThisCol = min(bestThisCol, max(breaks, survive));
            }
            bests[col] = bestThisCol;
        }

        return bests[n];
    }
};
```
Done. This answer is faster than ~50% of submissions.
Even though this is O(N^2) time and O(N) space, i think this might be an acceptable answer for an interview. Please add more if you can further optimize based on my thoughts.

