# Recursion
- Find the recurrence relation and take care of base cases
- Here the base cases would be if number of floors are 0 or 1 then number of moves are equals to number of floors
- Second  base condition if you are left with one egg you cannot drop the egg from any random floor you must start from 0th floor and increase the floor to find threshold floor
```
- Time Complexity : exponential (Consists of repeated sub problems)
- Space Complexity : O(1)
```
# Recursive Solution
```
class Solution {

    public int f(int eggs,int floors) {
        if(floors == 0 || floors == 1) return floors;
        if(eggs == 1) return floors;

        int ans = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        for(int i = 1;i <= floors;i++) {
            int min = Math.max( f(eggs-1,i-1) , f(eggs,floors - i));
            if(min < ans) ans = min;
        }
        return ans + 1;
    }
    public int twoEggDrop(int n) {
       int floors = n;
       int eggs = 2;
       return f(eggs,floors);
    }
}
```
# Memoization

- The recursive solution we will encounter with the sub problems which are already solved in recurrsive tree.It is the reason the time complexity is exponential in recursive solution
- So we use the datastructure to store the already solved sub problems solution and it use it when we encounter the same sub problem 
```
- Time Complexity : O( N * (K^2) )
- Space Complexity : O(N*K)
```
# Memoized Solution

```
class Solution {
    public int f(int eggs,int floors,int[][] memo) {
        if(floors == 0 || floors == 1) return floors;
        if(eggs == 1) return floors; 

        int ans = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        if(memo[eggs][floors] != -1) return memo[eggs][floors];

        for(int i = 1;i<=floors;i++) {
            int min = Math.max(f(eggs-1,i-1,memo),f(eggs,floors-i,memo));
            if(min < ans) ans = min;
        }

        return memo[eggs][floors] = ans+1;
    }
    public int twoEggDrop(int n) {
        int floors = n;
        int eggs = 2;
        int[][] memo = new int[eggs+1][floors+1];
        for(int[] arr: memo) Arrays.fill(arr,-1);
        return f(eggs,floors,memo);
    }
}
```
# DP One Row Optimization
- If we observed carefullly we are actually using the previous value to get the current value 
- In this case we can optimize it further by using 1-D array
```
- Time Complexity : O(N * logK)
- Space Complexity : O(N)
```
# DP Code
```
class Solution {

    public int twoEggDrop(int n) {
        int floors = n;
        int eggs = 2;
        int[] dp = new int[eggs+1];
        int moves = 0;
        for(moves = 0;dp[eggs] < floors;moves++) {
            for(int i = eggs;i>0;i--) {
                dp[i] += dp[i-1] + 1;
            }
        }
        return moves;
    }
}
```

