Base case 1: drop(1,N) -- N

Droping from a floor f has two outcomes
    1: Egg may break ---> have to move one floor down with one less egg. (There is no point in  trying                      from higher floors. So the num of remaining floors from where trying make sense is                      f-1.)
    2: Egg may not break ---> have to move one floor up with one less egg (Num of floors left would be 
            N-f as there is no point in  trying from lower floors. So the num of remaining floors from               where trying make sense is N-f.)

    Maximum of 1 and 2 is outcome for trying out drop from all floor OTHER THEN f.

The final out come of drop(E,N) is 1 + min(trying drop of E eggs from all floors 0 to N, except f). That '1' is the count for the current trial from current floor.
*/

class Solution {
public:
    int twoEggDrop(int n) {
        return bottomUp(n);
    }
    int bottomUp(int n){
        int e = 2;
        vector<vector<int>>DP(e+1,vector<int>(n+1,-1));
        for(int i = 0; i<n+1; ++i){
            DP[0][i] = 0;
        }
        for(int i = 0; i<e+1; ++i){
            DP[i][0] = 0;
        }
        for(int i = 0; i<n+1; ++i){
            DP[1][i] = i;
        }

        for(int floor = 1; floor<= n ; ++floor){
            int xx = floor;
            // One egg is base case. So start with 2. (Starting with one and trying to create
            // base case here ,, messes it up)
            for(int egg = 2; egg<= e ; ++egg){
                for(int drop = 1; drop<=floor ; ++drop){
                    xx = min(xx, max(DP[egg-1][drop-1], DP[egg][floor-drop]));
                }
                DP[egg][floor] = 1 + xx;
            }
        }        
        return DP[e][n];
    }

};
```

