solutions.content:
Let us assume you have only ONE egg and N floors to test. You could drop the egg from each floor starting from bottom to top. When the egg breaks on dropping, you know which floor you are on. So that way our answer is always ONE egg but ..... in the worst case, you would test the egg on each level from 1 to N.

In the above solution to test Floor-X you would move 2X levels,
1. you would move-up X floors and drop the egg
2. move-down X floors to pick the egg if unbroken, so you can test next floor

In total, you would move 2(1+2+3+....+N) that is **O(N^2) moves**

To understand how we reduce the moves, let us look at an example with **100 floors**. To build the best solution, we are working backwards so bear with me..

*Floor 100 - you must ideally have only ONE egg. You drop the egg, it breaks and voila.. don't care if the egg doesn't break. Either ways you are done testing all floors.*

*Floor 99 - you must ideally have TWO eggs because you would test 99th floor with the first egg. If the egg doesn't break, use the remaining ONE egg to test Floor-100. If the first egg breaks, use the remaining ONE egg to test Floor-98.*

*Floor 97 - you must ideally have THREE eggs because you would test 97th floor with the first egg. If the egg doesn't break, use the remaining TWO eggs at Floor-99. If the first egg breaks, use the remaining TWO eggs to test Floor-96 and Floor-95.*

*Floor 94 - you must ideally have FOUR eggs because you would test 94th floor with the first egg. If the egg doesn't break, use the remaining THREE eggs at Floor-97. If the first egg breaks, use the remaining THREE eggs to test Floor-93, Floor-92 and Floor-91.*

*Floor 90 - you must ideally have FIVE eggs because you would test 90th floor with the first egg. If the egg doesn't break, use the remaining FOUR eggs at Floor-94. If the first egg breaks, use the remaining FOUR eggs to test Floor-89, Floor-88 and Floor-87.*

Wait a second, while working backwards you can observe that 

*At Floor-100 you had ONE egg. Before that you were at Floor-99 which is 100-ONE
At Floor-99 you had TWO eggs. Before that you were at Floor-97 which is 99-TWO
At Floor-97 you had THREE eggs. Before that you were at Floor-94 which is 97-THREE
At Floor-94 you had FOUR eggs. Before that you were at Floor-90 which is 94-FOUR
At Floor-90 you had FIVE eggs. So where should you have been before? Floor-85 as it is 90-FIVE*

Hence the backward sequence of (Floor, Eggs) is (100, 1) > (99, 2) > (97, 3) > (94, 4) > (90, 5) > (85, 6) > (79, 7) > (72, 8) > (64, 9) > (55, 10) > (45, 11) > (34, 12) > (22, 13) > (9, 14) > and stop because at Floor-9 you have **14 eggs** and only 8 floors below to test.

You can test 9th floor with the first egg. If the egg doesn't break, use the remaining 13 eggs at Floor-22. If the first egg breaks, use the remaining 13 eggs to test Floor-8 to Floor-1.

So to generalize for N floors, you start with Floor-N with ONE egg and work your way backwards and stop at the floor where you have enough eggs to test all the floors below. 

You would move up N floors only once. In case an egg breaks, you would move #EGGS floors lower. In total, you would move only **O(N) moves**

**Java - O(n) time & O(1) space**
```
class Solution {
    public int twoEggDrop(int n) {
        int eggs = 1;
        while(eggs < n)
        {
            n -= eggs;
            eggs++;
        }

        return eggs;
    }
}
```

