solutions.content:
There are generic solutions for this problem which can account for more than 2 eggs, but this solution is greedy at implementation and does it in 1 dimensional DP.
Let's start off with recursive solution and then proceed to DP.
Intution :
Let's consider a sequence of moves, and let this sequence give the minimum no. of moves to find the target floor.
Now this sequence may start from any level between 1 to N. So, to find the first floor of sequence we loop for every floor while considering two cases :
1. Egg breaks at level i, this means we have only one egg left, so we can find floor f in no less than i-1 moves. 
2. Egg doesn't break at level i, this means we need to search for solution in N-i levels. 

We take maximum of the two cases (we need to consider worst case) at every iteration of loop.
Finally we take the minimum of all the moves that start from 1 to N.

Base cases : 
If there is only one floor, minimum moves is 1 as we need only one egg to find target floor.
If there is no floor, minimum moves is 0.

Recursive Solution :

			int twoEggDrop(int n) {
				if(n == 1 || n == 0) return n;
				int ans = INT_MAX;
				for(int i = 1; i <= n; i++)
				{
					int max_moves = 1 + max(i-1, twoEggDrop(n-i));
					ans = min(ans, max_moves);
				}       
				return ans;
				}        

The complexity is exponential, therefore we move forward to the DP solution.

Now we can store the recurring computation of minimum moves for finding f floor in total i floors. For this we take 1 dimensional array memo, such that memo[i] represents the minumum moves to find target floor in total i floors.
DP formula :

					memo[ i ] = INT_MAX
					memo[ i ] = for( j = 1 to i ) { min( memo[ i ], 1 + max( j - 1, memo[ i - j ] ) ) }

DP solution :

		int twoEggDrop(int n) {
        vector<int> memo(n+1, INT_MAX);
        memo[1] = 1, memo[0] = 0;
        for(int i = 2; i <= n; i++)
            for(int j = 1; j <= i; j++)
            {
                int max_moves = 1 + max(j-1, memo[i-j]);
                memo[i] = min(memo[i], max_moves);        
            }
        return memo[n];
    }

Time complexity : O(n^2)

